In J.R.R. Tolkien's iconic Lord of the Rings series, power is a pervasive and multifaceted theme that drives the narrative forward. The struggle for dominance and control is a constant undercurrent, (underlying) force that shapes the actions and motivations of characters throughout the story.

One of the primary explorations of power in the series is through the character of Sauron,1995, the primary antagonist of the story. His unyielding desire for domination and control over Middle-earth serves as a catalyst for the events of the narrative. The One Ring, which holds the key to his power,1982,, and is thus coveted by all who seek to wield it. This relentless pursuit of power ultimately becomes an all-consuming obsession, \that fuels the plot.

Conversely, A contrast to Sauron's malevolent grasp for power is the humble leadership of Aragorn (Strider). Unlike Sauron,1951, who seeks to impose his will upon others, (by) force and coercion,1993, on the other hand,, Aragorn1970 relies on persuasion, a1996nd collaboration to rally his followers. This juxtaposition highlights the distinction between benevolent authority and tyrannical dominion.
